urnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>pie</i> ‘merciful, compassionate, kind’, a variant of Old French, Anglo-Norman French <i>piu</i>, <i>peu</i>; see   Pew   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pew","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Pugh  .","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>pi(u)</i>, <i>piw</i>, <i>peu</i> ‘holy, pious’, also ‘merciful, kind, compassionate’."]},{"name":"Pyatt","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): nickname either from Middle English <i>piot</i> ‘magpie’ (Old French <i>pïot</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>pie</i>), commonly used to denote a chattering woman, or alternatively from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pyard</i>, an uncomplimentary term derived from the same Old French word + <i>-(h)ard</i>. Compare   Pye  .","Variant of   Piatt  , a surname of French and Walloon origin.","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Piatt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Pie","meanings":["English: variant of   Pye  , in part a cognate of 2 below.","French: nickname from Old French <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, perhaps given to a talkative person or someone who had a loud, chattering voice.","French (<b>Pié</b>): variant of   Piet   ‘foot’. Compare   Pease   and   Pee  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":31,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"John Pye Of Mynde was born in England as the son of John Pye and Elisabeth Scudamore. He married Agnes Andrews about 1443, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1550":"1550","about 1443":"umbes 1443","1480":"1480","1418":"1418","England":"England","The Mynde, Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Mynde Manor House, Kilpeck, Herefordshire, England":"Kilpeck, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1398–Male":"1398–Kuollut","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1550":"1550","about 1443":"noin 1443","1480":"1480","1418":"1418","England":"England","The Mynde, Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Mynde Manor House, Kilpeck, Herefordshire, England":"Kilpeck, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1398–Male":"1398–Décédé","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1550":"1550","about 1443":"environ 1443","1480":"1480","1418":"1418","England":"Angleterre","The Mynde, Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, Angleterre","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","Mynde Manor House, Kilpeck, Herefordshire, England":"Kilpeck, Herefordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"John Pye O